<div id="review_3395465705" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3395465705" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3395465705?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781978126763" href="/book/show/36714558-the-dream-of-a-ridiculous-man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3395465705" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15204382946314684763">“Killing myself was a matter of such indifference to me that I felt like waiting for a moment when it would make some difference.” <br/><br/>This is my favorite quote of Dostoyevsky‘s short story &quot;The dream of a ridiculous Man&quot; and captures its quintessence: the absurdity of human existence in the indifferent universe. Think of the absurdity of pushing a rock up a hill an infinite number of times, like described by Albert Camus in &quot;The myth of sisyphus&quot;. <br/><br/>Just like that the narrator of this story thinks of</span>
  <span id="freeText15204382946314684763" style="display:none">“Killing myself was a matter of such indifference to me that I felt like waiting for a moment when it would make some difference.” <br /><br />This is my favorite quote of Dostoyevsky‘s short story "The dream of a ridiculous Man" and captures its quintessence: the absurdity of human existence in the indifferent universe. Think of the absurdity of pushing a rock up a hill an infinite number of times, like described by Albert Camus in "The myth of sisyphus". <br /><br />Just like that the narrator of this story thinks of himself as a failure and his existence as ridiculous and absurd, desperate to the point of suicide. In an attempt to end his life he buys a revolver and plans to shoot himself in the head. First even the decision to pull the trigger seems too indifferent to him to actually execute. But once he finally made the decision to end his life and feels like nothing matters anymore, he refuses to help a child in need, which confuses him, because he realizes that his reaction mattered to someone else.<br /><br />He fell asleep and dreamed that he had killed himself, not by shooting himself in the head, but in the heart. He was buried, without loosing his awareness of his surroundings and then exhumed by a stranger. He traveled to a planet equal to earth, except that it was perfect and untainted, an utopian world. Science and technology were neither known nor necessary. People lived in harmony until his presence began to corrupt the society. He implored the people to crucify him, hoping that his sacrifice would return them to their previous state. Just like it happened to him on earth, the society started to think of him as ridiculous and mad. They threatened him with imprisonment, if he continued ranting about the possibility of an ideal society. He then wakes as a changed man. <br /><br />To me this is a story that confirms the absurdity of human existence and gives thoughts on suicide as a viable response, but at the same time demonstrates that happiness and and meaning can be attained in this world if one understands, that one should do good by his own conscious choosing.<br />As I interpret it, it also comments on the evolution of civilization and christianity. Dostoyevsky stresses that consciousness, knowledge and the ability to choose are what give any sense to life, because humanity had not regressed from paradise but progressed. God only had given the ability to do good, but it was the self given ability to choose to do good that made him progress from being unconscious and instinctive. Therefore living a moral life is not an element of human existence, but knowing to have a choice and that all choices are equal, because they result in the same fate, is the key to all happiness. <br /><br />I absolutely love this!<br /><br />The message I get is that we are merely human beings on this earth who can only conquer the absurdity of our own existence when we understand that our conscious mind transcends everything.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15204382946314684763" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


