        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer34577699" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6356986643097233079">This morning in class(!) I misread the text on some kid&apos;s shirt as being a book title (Being and Time, in fact) and thought about how strange it would be if people wore shirts advertising their favorite books instead of their favorite bands. Unless people actually do that...I&apos;m pretty sure I&apos;ve never seen it. That would be really pretentious. <br/>Why would a book shirt seem more pretentious than a band shirt? Is it because reading requires literacy and/or some form of intelligence, and all music req</span>
  <span id="freeText6356986643097233079" style="display:none">This morning in class(!) I misread the text on some kid's shirt as being a book title (Being and Time, in fact) and thought about how strange it would be if people wore shirts advertising their favorite books instead of their favorite bands. Unless people actually do that...I'm pretty sure I've never seen it. That would be really pretentious. <br />Why would a book shirt seem more pretentious than a band shirt? Is it because reading requires literacy and/or some form of intelligence, and all music requires is ears, which are more accessible?<br />I was looking through my books thinking about how funny their titles would look on a t-shirt, and decided that "Dream of a Ridiculous Man" could potentially be the name of some crappy screamo band. <br />Sorry, that was a bad review.</span>
