  <span id="freeText8076778628540699505" style="display:none">“<i>[the narrator] has the absolute fervor of a great prophet or a madman. but we do not know which of the two he is, for dostoyevsky has presented him both positively and negatively.</i>” <br />– elizabeth trahan<br /><br />not a groundbreaking plot, but masterful execution which tears down the deceptive simplicity. i did not know where to start with dostoyevsky, but these few pages of his concentrated talent, and the lovely translation by david magarshack, have laid a wonderful foundation. <br /><br /><i>“when they became wicked, they began talking of brotherhood and humanity and understood the meaning of those ideas. when they became guilty of crimes, they invented justice, and drew up whole codes of law, and to ensure the carrying out of their laws they erected a guillotine.”</i></span>
