  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3382446753" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3382446753" />
    <a title="Manaal Siddiqui" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43679659-manaal-siddiqui"><img alt="Manaal Siddiqui" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592482299p2/43679659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3382446753?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manaal Siddiqui" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manaal Siddiqui" href="/user/show/43679659-manaal-siddiqui">Manaal Siddiqui</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone interested in philosophy, nihilism, thought experiments, and the nature of existence.</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3382446753" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16266204109219363964">On the surface, Dostoevsky’s “The Dream of a Ridiculous Man” is about the transformation of a man contemplating suicide. The start of the story describes this man’s psychological state of mind— he apparently had a tough childhood and his resulting proud nature might be a coping strategy that helped him survive the ridicule from everyone around him. His pride leads to indifference and thus he reaches the conclusion that his life has no meaning, and subsequently decides to kill himself. However, h</span>
  <span id="freeText16266204109219363964" style="display:none">On the surface, Dostoevsky’s “The Dream of a Ridiculous Man” is about the transformation of a man contemplating suicide. The start of the story describes this man’s psychological state of mind— he apparently had a tough childhood and his resulting proud nature might be a coping strategy that helped him survive the ridicule from everyone around him. His pride leads to indifference and thus he reaches the conclusion that his life has no meaning, and subsequently decides to kill himself. However, he abandons this idea when he has a dream. A dream that plants an idea that completely changes him. The dream reveals his inner nature and we learn that, at its very core, his indifference was a consequence of his life’s troubles rather than a completely intellectual conclusion. <br /><br /> In the process of portraying this man’s transformation, Dostoevsky explores many ideas. His exploration occurs within an account of humanity’s own history: Adam and Eve living in paradise (represent the innocent humans on earth), then Satan misleads them (the dreaming man in this case), causing them to eat the apple (the ridiculous man corrupting humanity), which leads to humanity’s downfall. Dostoevsky highlights humanity’s eternal existential crisis— every person’s constant struggle to find meaning in life, to understand the purpose of their existence. <br /><br />“All are striving in the same direction anyway, from the sage to the lowest robber, only by different roads”<br /><br /> He sets out to prove that nihilism as a thought process is intrinsically flawed. One of the ways he does this is in the form of a thought experiment. <br /><br />“If I had lived before on the moon or on Mars and there had committed the most disgraceful and dishonorable action and had there been put to such shame and ignominy as one can only conceive and realize in dreams, in nightmares, and if, finding myself afterwards on earth, I were able to retain the memory of what I had done on the other planet and at the same time knew that I should never, under any circumstances, return there, then looking from the earth to the moon— should I care or not? Should I feel shame for that action or not?”<br /><br />Dostoevsky, being the genius that he is, indirectly answers this question, and in the process refutes Nietzsche’s attempt to sever connections to a higher order through his struggle against feelings of shame and guilt. The man has a dream (equivalent to going on another planet), and commits the gravest sin of all— he corrupts all of mankind, and is the reason for their downfall. When he wakes up (comes back to Earth) he is shaken to the core by his experience and is forever changed as a person. Thus, counter to nihilistic thought, Dostoevsky proves that man can never escape feelings of guilt and shame. <br /><br />Overall, I loved this book because the ridiculous man taught me that one does not need complicated theories of existence in order to be happy or live a meaningful life. He taught me to be content with life as it is, and to avoid a constant preoccupation with rationalizing the nature of existence and consciousness. <br /><br />“The consciousness of life is higher than life, the knowledge of the laws of happiness is higher than happiness— that is what one must content against.”<br /><br />I recommend this book to anyone interested in philosophy, nihilism, thought experiments, and the nature of existence.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16266204109219363964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


